  <h2 class="section-heading" id="try-it" data-jump-label="Try It Yourself">Try It: Create Your First Project</h2>
  <p class="section-description">Let's put this into practice. You'll create a simple Project that gives Claude persistent context about a recurring task you do at work.</p>

  <h3 style="font-size: 1.125rem; font-weight: 600; margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Step 1: Pick a Recurring Task</h3>
  <p class="section-description">Choose something you do at least weekly where you currently re-explain context to Claude each time. Examples:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Writing weekly status updates</li>
    <li>Reviewing customer tickets for patterns</li>
    <li>Drafting responses in a particular tone or format</li>
    <li>Analyzing data from a recurring report</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 style="font-size: 1.125rem; font-weight: 600; margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Step 2: Create the Project</h3>
  <ol class="steps-list">
    <li>In Claude, click the <strong>Projects</strong> icon in the left sidebar</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Create Project</strong></li>
    <li>Name it something descriptive (e.g., "Weekly Status Reports" or "Ticket Pattern Analysis")</li>
  </ol>

  <h3 style="font-size: 1.125rem; font-weight: 600; margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Step 3: Add Your Context</h3>
  <p class="section-description">In the Project's <strong>Custom Instructions</strong>, write 2-3 sentences that give Claude the background it needs. For example:</p>

  <div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #7c3aed 0%, #a855f7 100%); border-radius: 8px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; color: white;">
    <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
      <span style="font-size: 1.5rem;">üìù</span>
      <strong style="font-size: 1.125rem;">Example Project Instructions</strong>
    </div>
    <p style="margin: 0; line-height: 1.6; opacity: 0.95;">"I write a weekly status update for my team every Friday. The format should be: a 2-sentence summary at the top, then bullet points grouped by project. Tone should be direct and concise ‚Äî no fluff. My current projects are: Training Hub migration, Hackathon Week planning, and Sierra competitive response."</p>
  </div>

  <h3 style="font-size: 1.125rem; font-weight: 600; margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Step 4: Test It</h3>
  <p class="section-description">Start a new conversation inside the Project. Try a prompt like "Here are my notes from this week: [paste rough notes]. Draft my status update." Notice how Claude already knows the format, tone, and project list without you re-explaining.</p>

  <h3 style="font-size: 1.125rem; font-weight: 600; margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">What You Just Built</h3>
  <p class="section-description">This simple Project already demonstrates the three core advantages over regular chats:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li><strong>Persistent context</strong> ‚Äî Claude remembers your format and preferences across conversations</li>
    <li><strong>Reference materials</strong> ‚Äî You can upload docs, templates, or examples that Claude can always access</li>
    <li><strong>Reusable instructions</strong> ‚Äî Every conversation in this Project starts with your custom instructions applied</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="section-description">In the <strong>Builder</strong> path, you'll learn how to turn Projects into lightweight AI agents with skills, automation workflows, and team sharing.</p>

  <CalloutBox type="breakthrough" title="Preview: Projects as Basic Agents">
    We'll go much deeper on Projects in the Builder path. For now, understand that Projects are your gateway to more sophisticated AI collaboration‚Äîthe bridge between simple chats and full AI agents.
  </CalloutBox>

</ModuleLayout>
